Data

For this homework, we are going to use the Gapminder data on population (pop), GDP per capita (gdp), and life expectancy (lex). These data were downloaded and compiled using the gapminder_compile.Rmd script in the data folder.

Lets focus our attention on data from the past 100 years, between 1925 and 2025.

gapminder <- read_csv("data/gapminder.csv") %>% 
  clean_names() %>% 
  filter(between(year, 1925, 2025))

3. Which five countries have had the largest absolute population growth between 1925-2025? Show this as a table.

gapminder %>% 
  select(country, year, pop) %>% 
  pivot_wider(
    names_from = year,
    values_from = pop,
    names_prefix = "pop_"
  ) %>% 
  group_by(country) %>% 
  summarise(absolute_pop_growth = pop_2025 - pop_1925) %>% 
  arrange(desc(absolute_pop_growth)) %>% 
  filter(absolute_pop_growth >= 231082046)
## # A tibble: 5  2
##   country   absolute_pop_growth
##   <chr>                   <dbl>
## 1 India              1159459506
## 2 China               942354621
## 3 Indonesia           236035973
## 4 Pakistan            232594746
## 5 USA                 231082046


The five countries have had the largest absolute population growth between 1925-2025 are India, China, Indonesia, Pakistan, and the USA.

4. Make a plot that shows population growth over time for the top country you found in question #3.

gapminder %>% 
  select(country, year, pop) %>% 
  filter(country == "India") %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = year, y = pop)) +
  geom_line(color = "red") +
  geom_point(shape = 6) +
  labs(
    title = "Population Growth of India, 1925-2025",
    x = "Year",
    y = "Population"
  )

  1. Make a plot that shows the distribution of life expectancy for all countries in 1925 and 2025 (try using geom_density). What do you notice about the shift in life expectancy over time?
p <- gapminder %>% 
  select(country, year, lex) %>%
  filter(year %in% c(1925, 2025)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=lex))+
  geom_density() +
  geom_histogram(aes(y = after_stat(density)), alpha = 0.3) +
  facet_wrap(~year, ncol = 2) +
  labs(
    title = "Distribution of Global Life Expectency, 1925-2025",
    x = "Life Expectancy (Years)",
    y = NULL
  )
p + theme_stata()
## Warning: Removed 13 rows containing non-finite outside the scale range

Over time, the distribution of life expectancy shifted from the younger 20-40 years to the much older 60-80 years.

7. We are interested in the relationship between per capita GDP and life expectancy; i.e.does having more money help you live longer in 2025? Show this as a plot. (Suggestion! Remove Monaco as an extreme outlier.)

gapminder %>% 
  filter(country != "Monaco", year == 2025) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = lex, y = gdp)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE, color = "red") +
  scale_y_log10() +
  labs(
    title = "per Capita GDP vs. Life Expectancy in 2025",
    x = "Life Expectancy (Years)",
    y = "per Capita GDP (log10)"
  )

8. Which five countries have had the highest absolute GDP per capita growth over the past 50 years? Show this as a table. (Suggestion! Remove Monaco as an extreme outlier.)

gapminder %>%
  filter(country != "Monaco") %>% 
  select(country, year, gdp) %>% 
  pivot_wider(
    names_from = year,
    values_from = gdp,
    names_prefix = "gdp_"
  ) %>%
  group_by(country) %>% 
  summarise(absolute_gdp_growth = gdp_2025 - gdp_1975) %>% 
  arrange(desc(absolute_gdp_growth)) %>% 
  filter(absolute_gdp_growth >= 69382.41952)
## # A tibble: 5  2

The five countries that have had the highest absolute GDP per capita growth over the past 50 years are Singapore, Ireland, Luxembourg, Guyana, and Norway.

9. How does per capita GDP growth compare between these same five countries over the past 50 years? Show this as a plot.

p <- gapminder %>% 
  filter(country == c("Singapore", "Ireland", "Luxembourg", "Guyana", "Norway"), year >= 1975) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = year, y = gdp, color = country)) +
  geom_line() +
  scale_y_log10() +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(1975, 2025, by = 5), minor_breaks = NULL) +
  labs(
    title = "per Capita GDP of Top Five Richest Countries, 1975-2025",
    x = "Years",
    y = "per Capita GDP (log10)"
  )
p + theme_stata()+ 
  theme(legend.position = "right")
